	<h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-light leading-tight tracking-tight md:text-4xl">
		GitNexus Benchmark: Graph-Indexed Retrieval vs Claude Code's Native Exploration
	</h1>

	<blockquote class="mt-6">
		<p class="text-sm font-medium">TL;DR</p>
		<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			This note documents a structured comparison of two codebase exploration strategies applied
			to the same architectural question on a mid-sized Flutter project: Claude Code's native
			heuristic-guided tool invocation (the Explore subagent in very thorough mode), and
			<strong>GitNexus</strong>, a graph-indexed code intelligence layer backed by
			<strong>KuzuDB</strong>, an embedded columnar property graph database [1]. The graph-indexed
			approach reduced total session cost by 25% ($0.52 to $0.39), reduced tool calls by
			approximately 68% (38 to ~12), and consumed 43% fewer tokens, without loss of
			architectural depth. The analysis additionally examines where the current GitNexus index
			ceiling lies and what index conditions are required to realize its full retrieval potential.
		</p>
	</blockquote>

	<!-- Context / Motivation -->
	<section class="mt-10">
		<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
			Evaluating retrieval tooling for architectural reasoning is not a straightforward exercise.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Most retrieval benchmarks operate on document-centric corpora (legal texts, support ticket
			archives, technical documentation) where relevance correlates meaningfully with semantic
			proximity. A query about authentication surfaces documents that discuss authentication.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Codebase retrieval operates under materially different conditions. The questions that matter
			most to a software architect are not semantic but structural: which components depend on this
			interface, what execution path connects a user action to data persistence, what is the
			blast radius of modifying a given abstraction. These questions are, in a precise sense,
			graph traversal problems. The degree to which a retrieval system can answer them depends
			less on embedding quality and more on whether relational structure is preserved in the index
			at all.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			This benchmark evaluates two retrieval strategies against this class of structural query:
			Claude Code's native tool-based exploration and GitNexus graph-indexed retrieval.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- The fundamental limitation of vector search for code -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">The fundamental limitation of vector-based retrieval for code</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Vector-based retrieval encodes text as geometric representations in high-dimensional space
			and retrieves candidates by cosine similarity to a query embedding. This approach is
			well-suited to unstructured prose where vocabulary co-occurrence and semantic overlap
			reliably approximate relevance.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Three structural properties of source code systematically undermine this assumption.
		</p>

		<div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
			<div class="rounded-lg bg-muted/50 p-5">
				<p class="font-medium">Chunking severs cross-file relationships</p>
				<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
					Vector indexing requires decomposing files into bounded chunks. This decomposition
					necessarily destroys the edges that give code its meaning: caller-callee relationships,
					import chains, interface implementations. A function's chunk encodes its body; it does
					not encode that it is the sole upstream path for write operations, a fact that resides
					in its callers, not in the function itself.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg bg-muted/50 p-5">
				<p class="font-medium">Semantic proximity does not imply structural connectivity</p>
				<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
					Two components that are tightly coupled in execution may be semantically distant. An
					authentication lifecycle handler and a sync connection provider share little vocabulary
					yet one directly triggers the other at a critical point in the application flow. Their
					relationship is an edge in a call graph. It is not recoverable from geometric proximity
					in embedding space.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg bg-muted/50 p-5">
				<p class="font-medium">Retrieval imprecision degrades to context inflation</p>
				<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
					When vector retrieval fails to surface precisely relevant files, the compensating
					strategy is to expand context: loading additional files and delegating the filtering
					burden to the language model. The empirical consequence is visible in the benchmark
					data below, where cache reads constituted 88-96% of total token consumption across both
					experimental runs. The model was not retrieving targeted information; it was scanning
					an inflated context window to locate relevant content.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Claude Code's native exploration approach -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Claude Code's native codebase exploration</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Before examining GitNexus, it is important to characterize the baseline accurately. Claude
			Code's Explore subagent does not perform random or undirected traversal. It executes a
			principled, heuristic-guided iterative retrieval strategy using three primary tools:
			<code>Glob</code> for pattern-based file discovery, <code>Grep</code> for keyword and
			symbol search within file contents, and <code>Read</code> for file ingestion.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The process is iterative and reactive. An initial set of search terms, derived from the
			query, drives the first round of Glob and Grep invocations. The content of discovered
			files yields new candidate symbols and filenames, which drive subsequent rounds. This
			continues until coverage is deemed sufficient, accumulating discovered files into the
			model's context window as the session progresses.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			This strategy is effective and general-purpose. Its cost structure, however, reflects its
			reactive nature: each iteration requires a model inference step to determine what to search
			for next, and file content must be loaded in full to yield new search terms. The discovery
			overhead scales with codebase complexity and with the number of indirect relationships
			between relevant components.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- What GitNexus is -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">GitNexus: graph-indexed codebase retrieval</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			GitNexus indexes a codebase as a labeled property graph rather than a vector store or a
			flat file corpus. Symbols (functions, classes, interfaces, modules) are represented as
			nodes with typed properties. Relationships (call edges, import edges, inheritance edges,
			implementation edges) are represented as directed, labeled arcs. Execution flows, where
			indexed, become traversable paths through the graph.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			This representation preserves precisely the structural information that chunked vector
			indices discard. A query against the graph returns nodes matching a concept and their
			relationship neighborhood: not "text similar to this description" but "the exact files
			participating in this feature, along with the typed edges connecting them."
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			GitNexus exposes this graph through a Model Context Protocol server, allowing a language
			model to issue structured graph queries during a session without reverting to sequential
			file traversal.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- KuzuDB internals -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">The storage engine: KuzuDB</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The performance characteristics of GitNexus's graph queries are determined in substantial
			part by its underlying storage engine: <strong>KuzuDB</strong>, an embedded columnar
			property graph database developed at the University of Waterloo and formally described by
			Feng et al. at CIDR 2023 [1]. KuzuDB has been positioned in the literature as a graph
			analogue to DuckDB, an in-process, analytically optimized engine that eliminates the
			network overhead of client-server graph databases such as Neo4j.
		</p>

		<h3 class="mt-8 text-base font-semibold">Columnar adjacency storage via CSR</h3>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			KuzuDB stores graph structure using Compressed Sparse Row (CSR) adjacency indices [1].
			Node properties are stored in columnar disk files, consistent with OLAP storage conventions.
			Edge relationships are encoded as double-indexed CSR structures: for each source node, the
			set of destination node IDs and associated edge properties are stored contiguously on disk.
			This layout enables edge traversal in time proportional to node degree, avoiding the
			hash-based lookups or B-tree traversals required by relation-table designs.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			For code intelligence, this is structurally significant. A query of the form "find all
			callers of function <em>f</em> across the call graph" resolves to a reverse-edge traversal
			followed by a property filter, an operation that the CSR index can execute without scanning
			unrelated portions of the symbol table.
		</p>

		<h3 class="mt-8 text-base font-semibold">Factorized query execution</h3>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The more consequential architectural contribution is KuzuDB's factorized query processor,
			grounded in worst-case optimal join theory [2, 3]. Traditional binary join execution
			materializes intermediate result tables at each join step; in many-to-many graph patterns
			this produces intermediate results that are exponentially larger than the final output, a
			well-documented pathology in graph workloads [1].
		</p>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			KuzuDB's multiway ASP-Join (Accumulate-Semijoin-Probe) operator processes joins
			column-at-a-time rather than relation-at-a-time, maintaining factorized representations
			of intermediate results [1]. Redundant tuple replication is suppressed; intermediate result
			sets are reported to compress by 50-100x on multi-hop queries compared to binary join
			execution [1]. This is directly relevant to GitNexus: queries like "find the full
			dependency subgraph of component <em>X</em>" or "enumerate all execution paths from
			entry point <em>A</em> to persistence layer <em>B</em>" are exactly the cyclic,
			multi-hop patterns that factorized execution handles efficiently.
		</p>

		<h3 class="mt-8 text-base font-semibold">Vectorized processing and in-process execution</h3>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Query execution proceeds through vectorized batches (default capacity: 2,048 values per
			vector, sized to fit CPU L3 cache), enabling SIMD optimization and reducing interpreted
			overhead per tuple, consistent with columnar OLAP processing principles described by
			Abadi et al. [4]. Multi-core parallelism is managed through a task scheduler using
			morsel-driven parallelism with minimal synchronization overhead [1].
		</p>
		<p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Critically, KuzuDB is embedded: it runs in-process within the GitNexus MCP server with no
			network round-trips between the graph query engine and the calling application. For
			interactive agent sessions where latency compounds across tool calls, this distinction
			is material.
		</p>

		<div class="mt-6 rounded-lg border p-5">
			<p class="text-sm font-medium">How GitNexus uses KuzuDB</p>
			<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
				GitNexus runs a multi-phase indexing pipeline over a repository: tree-sitter extracts
				abstract syntax trees from source files, which are mapped to a property graph schema
				(files, symbols, and typed relationship edges), persisted into KuzuDB, and annotated
				with precomputed metadata (community assignments, confidence scores). At query time,
				the MCP server translates a natural-language concept query into a KuzuDB Cypher query,
				returning the relevant symbol nodes and their relationship neighborhoods directly,
				without loading any source file into the language model's context window.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Benchmark methodology -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Benchmark methodology</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The evaluation subject was a mid-sized Flutter project implementing an offline-first sync
			architecture: bidirectional real-time synchronization with a remote service, local SQLite
			persistence via a typed ORM layer, and Riverpod-managed application state. The query posed
			was architectural in scope, examining how the sync integration functions end-to-end, from
			application bootstrap through credential acquisition to upstream and downstream data
			exchange.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Two experimental conditions were evaluated in sequence. The first condition employed Claude
			Code's Explore subagent in very thorough mode, representing the default high-coverage
			exploration strategy. The second condition used GitNexus as the primary discovery layer,
			with source file reads performed only on files the graph query identified as relevant.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Token consumption and session cost were measured as deltas from usage telemetry snapshots
			captured immediately before and after each experimental run, isolating per-session overhead
			from cumulative baseline consumption.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Results -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Results</h2>

		<div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto">
			<table class="w-full text-sm">
				<thead>
					<tr class="border-b text-left">
						<th class="pb-3 pr-8 font-medium">Metric</th>
						<th class="pb-3 pr-8 font-medium">Claude Code Explore (baseline)</th>
						<th class="pb-3 font-medium">GitNexus</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody class="text-muted-foreground">
					<tr class="border-b">
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Total session cost</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">$0.52</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">$0.39</td>
					</tr>
					<tr class="border-b">
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Total tokens consumed</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">1,573,096</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">889,126</td>
					</tr>
					<tr class="border-b">
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Cache read tokens (% of total)</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">1,386,972 (88%)</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">858,166 (96%)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr class="border-b">
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Tool calls issued</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">38</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">~12</td>
					</tr>
					<tr class="border-b">
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Elapsed time</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">~105 seconds</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">~2-3 minutes</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">Source files read</td>
						<td class="py-3 pr-8">~10</td>
						<td class="py-3 font-medium text-foreground">~10</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>

		<p class="mt-6 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The most informative observation is that both conditions read approximately the same number
			of source files. The reduction in token consumption and tool call overhead did not derive
			from reading less; it derived from spending fewer inference steps to determine <em>what</em>
			to read.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The Explore subagent's 38 tool calls reflect its iterative discovery methodology: Glob
			invocations across naming patterns, Grep calls across keyword sets, Read operations on
			candidate files, and subsequent search refinement conditioned on file content. The GitNexus
			condition issued a single <code>gitnexus_query</code> call that returned 9 relevant files
			directly, with no false positives requiring further elimination. Remaining tool calls
			consisted of targeted Read operations on the identified files.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The baseline condition additionally employed a secondary Haiku subagent for the indexing
			pass: 158k cache tokens created and 1M cache tokens read, accounting for $0.32 of the
			$0.52 total. The GitNexus condition required no secondary model; discovery overhead was
			absorbed by the pre-built KuzuDB index rather than delegated to a subagent at query time.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Ceiling and limitations -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Index fidelity and the current ceiling</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The GitNexus index at the time of this evaluation contained 338 symbols and 322
			relationship edges, but <strong>0 indexed execution flows</strong>.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Execution flows constitute the highest-value artifact a graph index can provide for
			architectural reasoning. A complete flow entry for the sync initialization path, covering
			authentication event through connection establishment to active data exchange, would allow
			the architectural query to be answered in a single KuzuDB path traversal, without reading
			any source file. This is precisely the capability that KuzuDB's factorized join execution
			and CSR-indexed adjacency structures are architected to serve efficiently [1].
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Without flows, the graph functioned as a high-precision file locator rather than a full
			architectural reasoning substrate. It eliminated the iterative discovery overhead but did
			not eliminate the reading burden. The analytical synthesis required to answer the
			end-to-end architectural question still depended on traversing source files, identical
			in structure to the baseline condition, though more precisely targeted.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Projected forward: with flows fully indexed, the 5-6 source file reads required for
			architectural synthesis would be replaceable by a single path query. Estimated cost for
			the same task under that condition would likely fall to the $0.25-0.30 range, with
			proportional reductions in elapsed time and model reasoning load.
		</p>

		<div class="mt-6 rounded-lg border p-5">
			<p class="text-sm font-medium">Index health verification</p>
			<p class="mt-1 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
				Prior to relying on GitNexus for execution flow queries, verify that the index has been
				built with process analysis enabled. Run <code>gitnexus analyze</code> and inspect the
				reported process count. An index reporting 0 processes will provide file discovery
				benefits but will not support path traversal. The file discovery benefit alone, as
				this benchmark demonstrates, remains material.
			</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Architectural implications -->
	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold">Architectural implications</h2>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The results support a broader principle with practical consequences for teams adopting
			AI-assisted development at architectural scale.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Claude Code's native exploration strategy is sound and effective for general-purpose
			investigation. Its limitation is structural: because it discovers relationships reactively
			through iterative search, it incurs inference overhead proportional to the number of
			indirect connections between relevant components. On complex architectures such as
			distributed sync systems, multi-layered dependency graphs, and event-driven flows, that
			overhead compounds.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			Graph-indexed retrieval addresses this at the index layer. By precomputing the symbol graph
			using KuzuDB's CSR adjacency structures and factorized join execution [1], GitNexus amortizes
			the relational discovery cost across all subsequent queries. Individual query sessions inherit
			a precomputed structural view of the codebase rather than reconstructing it from scratch
			through iterative tool invocation.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			The overhead of graph indexing (index construction time, maintenance across commits,
			tooling integration) represents a fixed cost that amortizes favorably on codebases where
			architectural questions are asked frequently. For smaller codebases or single-file queries,
			the differential remains marginal.
		</p>
		<p class="mt-4 leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
			For the classes of projects encountered in production, including offline-first mobile
			applications, distributed sync architectures, and multi-service backends with complex
			dependency graphs, the dominant questions are relational: "what calls this," "what depends
			on this," "where does this data originate." These are graph questions. The appropriate
			retrieval substrate is a graph index.
		</p>
	</section>

